# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: conservation-in-scotland
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:conservation-in-scotland/30-by-30] US$5 billion in funding for a project called the "Protecting Our Planet Challenge" was announced for the initiative in September 2021.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/30-by-30] In December 2022, 30 by 30 was agreed at the COP15 meeting of the Convention on Biological Diversity, and became a target of the Kunming-Montreal Global Biodiversity Framework.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/30-by-30] This includes the G7 and European Union.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/30-by-30] The initiative has attracted controversy over indigenous rights issues.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/30-by-30] As of May 2026, 17.3% of terrestrial land and inland waters and 9.8% of marine areas are protected.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/30-by-30] Including OECM's (Other Effective Area-based Conservation Measures) the percent of protected areas are 18.4% of terrestrial and inland waters and 10.0% of marine areas.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/30-by-30] The European Commission's Biodiversity strategy for 2030 was proposed on May 20, 2020, as the European Union's contribution to a post-2020 global biodiversity framework.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/30-by-30] The plan includes turning 30% of EU territory to protected area by 2030 and 10% to strictly protected area.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/30-by-30] However as of 2023 EU is not on track to meet the targets.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/30-by-30] The biodiversity strategy is a core part of the European Green Deal, and also intended to support green recovery from the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/30-by-30] In July 2023 after many debates the European parliament adopted a version of the Nature restoration law, aiming to restore nature on 20% of the territory of the European Union by 2030.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/30-by-30] In 2024, the European Union passed a nature restoration law aiming to restore 20% of degraded ecosystems by 2030 and 100% by 2050.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/30-by-30] On January 27, 2021, President Joe Biden issued an executive order on "Tackling the Climate Crisis at Home and Abroad".
[src:conservation-in-scotland/30-by-30] Participating federal agencies included the U.S.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/30-by-30] Department of Commerce, and Council on Environmental Quality.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/30-by-30] The order also established a California Biodiversity Collaborative composed of representatives of government agencies, Native tribes, experts, and other stakeholders.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/30-by-30] The official report, *Pathways to 30x30 California*, was issued by the California Natural Resources Agency on 22 April 2022.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/30-by-30] Implementation of the 30 by 30 target has progressed unevenly, and researchers caution that simply increasing the extent of protected areas is not sufficient to halt biodiversity loss.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/30-by-30] Some conservationists argue that the 30% figure lacks a clear scientific justification and risks being treated as a symbolic or political benchmark rather than a threshold grounded in ecological evidence.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/30-by-30] At the same time, other researchers and advocacy groups contend that 30% may in fact be too low to secure long‑term ecological integrity, and point to proposals such as the "Half‑Earth" concept, which calls for roughly 50% of terrestrial and marine realms to be conserved in some form.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/30-by-30] A further concern relates to the quality and effectiveness of protection once areas are designated.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/30-by-30] Researchers and NGOs have highlighted the persistence of so‑called "paper parks": protected areas that exist in law but lack adequate funding, staffing or enforcement, allowing activities such as poaching, illegal logging, or unregulated development to continue.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/30-by-30] Modelling work by Kuempel et al. suggests that, for exploited species, improving enforcement and management within existing protected areas can in many cases deliver greater conservation benefits than simply expanding the network’s total area without a corresponding increase in resources.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/30-by-30] Taken together, this literature underlines that meeting percentage‑based targets without adequate governance capacity risks diluting scarce conservation resources.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/30-by-30] Other research has examined conditions under which expanding protected areas can still be beneficial even when management budgets do not increase.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/30-by-30] Their results suggest that, in landscapes where human pressures are spatially clumped near reserve boundaries, strategically increasing the size of protected areas can create more secure habitat refuges even without proportional increases in staffing or enforcement.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/30-by-30] In practice, the 30 by 30 commitment has also prompted debate over how "protected" or "conserved" areas are defined for monitoring and reporting purposes.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/30-by-30] Implementation of the 30 by 30 target has also raised concerns about “green grabbing” and green colonialism in the way new protected and conserved areas may be established.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/30-by-30] Similar critiques have been echoed by human rights organisations and researchers who argue that percentage-based conservation targets can replicate earlier "fortress conservation" models if they are implemented through top-down land designations that disregard customary tenure and existing uses.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/30-by-30] More broadly, some Indigenous organisations have criticised the way 30 by 30 has been promoted and negotiated, arguing that it risks appropriating Indigenous lands under the guise of biodiversity conservation.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/30-by-30] The COP15 included 196 parties in negotiations, with competing views regarding the adoption of the 30 by 30 target being wide-spread and well documented.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/30-by-30] The resulting agreement of the conference, the Convention on Biological Diversity, was signed by every party, with the exception of two: the United States and the Vatican.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/30-by-30] Towards the end of the talks, a negotiator from Democratic Republic of the Congo raised objections to the agreement, citing a lack of funding separate from the current Global Environment Facility (GEF).
[src:conservation-in-scotland/30-by-30] After a delay, COP15 president and Chinese environment minister Huang Runqiu overruled the objection due to a legal technicality, resulting in the passage of the agreement.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/30-by-30] Delegates from the DRC, Cameroon, and Uganda were reportedly displeased with the outcome.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/30-by-30] After the agreement was passed, the DRC's government announced that it would not recognize it as valid.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/abbeys-and-priories-in-scotland-p01] This **list of monastic houses in Scotland** is a catalogue of the abbeys, priories, friaries and other monastic religious houses of Scotland.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/abbeys-and-priories-in-scotland-p01] In this article alien houses are included, as are smaller establishments such as cells and notable monastic granges (particularly those with resident monks).
[src:conservation-in-scotland/abbeys-and-priories-in-scotland-p01] The numerous monastic hospitals *per se* are not included here unless at some time the foundation had, or was purported to have, the status or function of an abbey, priory, friary or preceptory/commandery.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/abbeys-and-priories-in-scotland-p01] The geographical co-ordinates provided are sourced from details provided by the Royal Commission on the Ancient and Historical Monuments in Scotland (RCAHMS) and Ordnance Survey publications.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/abbeys-and-priories-in-scotland-p01] The list is presented alphabetically by council area.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/abbeys-and-priories-in-scotland-p01] Foundations are listed alphabetically within each area.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/abbeys-and-priories-in-scotland-p01] Locations with names in *italics* indicate probable duplication (misidentification with another location) or non-existent foundations (either erroneous reference or proposed foundation never implemented.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/abbeys-and-priories-in-scotland-p01] Communities/provenance: shows the status and communities existing at each establishment, together with such dates as having been established as well as the fate of the establishment after dissolution, and the current status of the site.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/abbeys-and-priories-in-scotland-p01] Formal name or dedication: shows the formal name of the establishment or the person in whose name the church is dedicated, where known.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/abbeys-and-priories-in-scotland-p01] Alternative names: some of the establishments have had alternative names over the course of time.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/abbeys-and-priories-in-scotland-p01] In order to assist in text-searching, such alternatives in name or spelling have been provided.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/action-to-protect-rural-scotland] APRS campaigns on a range of issues relating to the countryside in Scotland, including national parks, green belts, and the circular economy.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/action-to-protect-rural-scotland] APRS was formerly known as the **Association for the Preservation of Rural Scotland**, but changed its name in 2023.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/action-to-protect-rural-scotland] The inaugural meeting of what would become the Association for the Preservation of Rural Scotland took place in Spring 1927.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/action-to-protect-rural-scotland] In 1929 APRS were offered the Loch Dee estate for purchase, but under the terms of its constitution it did not have the power to own land.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/action-to-protect-rural-scotland] The issue was discussed with the National Trust, but it was decided that Scotland should have its own organisation.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/action-to-protect-rural-scotland] APRS council decided at a meeting in July 1930 to proceed with establishing a separate organisation in Scotland, having decided not to expand the remit of APRS to enable it to hold land.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/action-to-protect-rural-scotland] The National Trust for Scotland would be officially incorporated on 1 May 1931.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/action-to-protect-rural-scotland] APRS played a central role in early campaigns for National Parks in Scotland.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/action-to-protect-rural-scotland] Proposals to establish a National Park in Scotland were first discussed in the pages of Scots Magazine, beginning with an article by the access campaigner Ernest A.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/action-to-protect-rural-scotland] The discussion on Scots Magazine prompted APRS to organise a conference on national parks on 4 June 1929.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/action-to-protect-rural-scotland] The Conference would lead to the establishment of a 'Scottish Forest Reserve Committee', which would later propose establishing a National Trust body in Scotland.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/action-to-protect-rural-scotland] APRS would later establish the Scottish Council on National Parks in 1942.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/action-to-protect-rural-scotland] In the 1920s and 1930s APRS was involved in campaigns against various hydro schemes in the north of Scotland which had been proposed by private companies.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/action-to-protect-rural-scotland] One of those, the Grampain Scheme, would have involved the "obliteration" of the Falls of Glomach, another scheme proposed the diversion of waters from many glens north of the Great Glen in order to supply a large hydro power station which would have been built at Kinloch Hourn.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/action-to-protect-rural-scotland] APRS are involved in campaigning for additional National Parks in Scotland, working closely with the Scottish Campaign for National Parks (SCNP).
[src:conservation-in-scotland/action-to-protect-rural-scotland] The organisation supported proposals for a third Scottish National Park in Galloway before the plans were dropped by the Scottish Government in 2025.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/action-to-protect-rural-scotland] APRS have been working on the Circular Economy as part of its ‘Have you Got the Bottle’ campaign since 2015.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/action-to-protect-rural-scotland] As part of this campaign APRS has argued for a deposit return scheme in Scotland.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/action-to-protect-rural-scotland] A planned scheme in Scotland was cancelled in 2023.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/action-to-protect-rural-scotland] Action to Protect Rural Scotland (APRS) has campaigned for the protection and enhancement of Scotland’s designated green belts.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/action-to-protect-rural-scotland] Their work involves producing guidance (such as their *Green Belts Advice Note*), supporting community campaigners through the “Green Belts Alliance”, and intervening in planning processes to protect green-belt land from piecemeal erosion and unsustainable development.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The **Acts of Union** refer to two acts of Parliament, one by the Parliament of Scotland in March 1707, followed shortly thereafter by an equivalent act of the Parliament of England.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] They put into effect the international Treaty of Union agreed on 22 July 1706, which politically joined the Kingdom of England and Kingdom of Scotland into a single "political state" named Great Britain, with Queen Anne as its sovereign.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The English and Scottish acts of ratification took effect on 1 May 1707, creating the new kingdom, with its parliament based in the Palace of Westminster.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The two countries had shared a monarch since the "personal" Union of the Crowns in 1603, when James VI of Scotland inherited the English throne from his cousin Elizabeth I to become (in addition) 'James I of England', styled James VI and I.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Prior to 1603, England and Scotland had different monarchs, but when Elizabeth I died without children, she was succeeded as King of England by her distant relative, James VI of Scotland.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] After her death, the two Crowns were held in personal union by James (reigning as James VI and I), who announced his intention to unite the two realms.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The 1603 Union of England and Scotland Act established a joint Commission to agree terms, but the Parliament of England was concerned this would lead to an absolutist structure similar to that of Scotland.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] James was forced to withdraw his proposals, but used the royal prerogative to take the title "King of Great Britain".
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Attempts to revive the project of union in 1610 were met with hostility.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] English opponents such as Sir Edwin Sandys argued that changing the name of England "were as yf [*sic*] to make a conquest of our name, which was more than ever the Dane or Norman could do".
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Instead, James set about creating a unified Church of Scotland and England, as the first step towards a centralised, Unionist state.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] However, despite both being nominally Episcopal in structure, the two were very different in doctrine; the Church of Scotland, or kirk, was Calvinist in doctrine, and viewed many Church of England practices as little better than Catholicism.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] As a result, attempts to impose religious policy by James and his son Charles I ultimately led to the 1639–1651 Wars of the Three Kingdoms.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The 1639–1640 Bishops' Wars confirmed the primacy of the Scots kirk, and established a Covenanter government in Scotland.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The Scots remained neutral when the First English Civil War began in 1642, before becoming concerned at the impact on Scotland of an English Royalist victory.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Presbyterian leaders like Argyll viewed union as a way to ensure free trade between England and Scotland, and preserve a Scots Presbyterian kirk.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Under the 1643 Solemn League and Covenant, the Scots Parliament agreed to provide military support to its English counterpart in return for a united Presbyterian church, but did not explicitly commit to political union.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] As the war progressed, Scots and English Presbyterians increasingly viewed the English Independents, and associated radical groups like the Levellers, as a bigger threat than the Royalists.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Both Royalists and Presbyterians agreed monarchy was divinely ordered, but disagreed on the nature and extent of Royal authority over the church.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] When Charles I surrendered in 1646, an English pro-Royalist faction known as the Engagers allied with their former enemies to restore him to the English throne.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] After defeat in the 1647–1648 Second English Civil War, Scotland was occupied by English troops, which were withdrawn once those whom Cromwell held responsible had been replaced by the Kirk Party.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] In December 1648, Pride's Purge paved the way for the Trial of Charles I in England by excluding MPs who opposed it.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Following the execution of Charles I in January 1649, and establishment of the Commonwealth of England, the Scots Kirk Party proclaimed Charles II King of Scots and England and, in the 1650 Treaty of Breda, resolved to restore him to the English throne.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Instead, defeat in the Anglo-Scottish War resulted in Scotland's incorporation into the Commonwealth in 1653, largely driven by Cromwell's determination to break the power of the Scots kirk.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The 1652 Tender of Union was followed on 12 April 1654 by *An Ordinance by the Protector for the Union of England and Scotland,* creating the Commonwealth of England and Scotland.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] It was ratified by the Second Protectorate Parliament on 26 June 1657, creating a single Parliament in Westminster, with 30 representatives each from Scotland and Ireland added to the existing English members.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] While integration into the Commonwealth established free trade between Scotland and England, the economic benefits were diminished by the costs of military occupation.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Both Scotland and England associated union with heavy taxes and military rule; it had little popular support in either Country, and the union was dissolved after the Restoration of Charles II in 1660.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The Scottish economy was badly damaged by the (protectionist) English Navigation Acts of 1660 and 1663 and England's wars with the Dutch Republic, Scotland's major export market.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] An Anglo-Scots Trade Commission was set up in January 1668 but the English had no interest in making concessions, as the Scots had little to offer in return.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] In 1669, Charles II revived talks on "political union"; his motives may have been to weaken Scotland's commercial and political links with the Dutch, still seen as an enemy and complete the work of his grandfather James I and VI.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] On the Scottish side, the proposed union received parliamentary support, boosted by the desire to ensure free trade.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Continued opposition meant these negotiations were abandoned by the end of 1669.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The Convention of the Estates issued an address to William and Mary "as both kingdomes are united in one head and soveraigne so they may become one body pollitick, one nation to be represented in one parliament", reserving "our church government, as it shall be established at the tyme of the union".
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] William and Mary were supportive of the idea but it was opposed both by the Presbyterian majority in Scotland and the English Parliament.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Episcopacy in Scotland was abolished in 1690, alienating a significant part of the political class; it was this element that later formed the bedrock of opposition to Union.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The 1690s were a time of economic hardship in Europe as a whole and Scotland in particular, a period now known as the Seven ill years which led to strained relations with England.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] In 1698, the Company of Scotland Trading to Africa and the Indies received a charter to raise capital through public subscription.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The Company invested in the Darién scheme, an ambitious plan funded almost entirely by Scottish investors to build a colony on the Isthmus of Panama for trade with East Asia.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The scheme was a disaster; the losses of over £150,000 severely impacted the Scottish commercial system.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The International Treaty, and English and Scots acts of ratification of Union may be seen within a wider European context of increasing state centralisation during the late 17th and early 18th centuries, including the monarchies of France, Sweden, Denmark-Norway and Spain.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] While there were exceptions, such as the Dutch Republic or the Republic of Venice, the trend was clear.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The dangers of the monarch using one parliament against the other first became apparent in 1647 and 1651.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] It resurfaced during the 1679 to 1681 Exclusion Crisis, caused by English resistance to the Catholic prince James (later James II of England, James VII of Scots) succeeding his brother Charles II.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] It then went beyond ensuring James's succession to the Scots throne by explicitly stating the aim was to make his exclusion from the English throne impossible without "the fatall and dreadfull consequences of a civil war".
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The issue reappeared during the 1688 Dutch invasion and *coup d'etat* (subsequently entitled as "the Glorious Revolution").
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The English Convention Parliament generally supported replacing James with his Protestant daughter Mary, holding to their "legal fiction" that James, by fleeing to France, had abandoned his English subjects and "abdicated".
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] They initially resisted making her Dutch husband William of Orange joint ruler but relented, "fearing the return of James" only when William threatened to take his troops and fleet and return to the Netherlands, and Mary refused to rule without him.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] In Scotland, it became a Constitutional issue.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The fact that King James had not been present in Scotland meant that the question of abdication need not arise.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] On 4 April 1689 a Convention of the Three Estates of Scotland (sister body to the Parliament of Scotland) declared that James "had acted irregularly" by assuming regal power (government) "without ever taking the Coronation Oath required by Scots Law".
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Thus, he had "FOREFALTED [forfeited] the Right to the Scots Crown, and the Scots Throne is become vacant".
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] "Scots monarchs derived legitimacy from the Convention of the Estates", later declared a Parliament of Scotland, not God, thus ending the principle of divine right of kings.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Conflict over control of the kirk between Presbyterians and Episcopalians and William's position as a fellow Calvinist put him in a much stronger position.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] He originally insisted on retaining Episcopacy, and the Committee of the Articles, an unelected body that controlled what legislation Parliament could debate.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Both would have given the Crown far greater control than in England but he withdrew his demands due to the 1689–1692 Jacobite Rising.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] 2. the Convention of the Estates was a parliament and so parliament could just rewrite it.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Here is the Claim of Right understood and upheld for its secular constitutional provisions quite as much as for its religious provisions.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The English succession was provided for by the English Act of Settlement 1701, which ensured that the monarch of England would be a Protestant member of the House of Hanover.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Until the union of parliaments, the Scottish throne might be inherited by a different successor after Queen Anne, who had said in her first speech to the English parliament that a union was "very necessary".
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The Scottish Act of Security 1704, however, was passed after the English parliament, without consultation with Scotland, had designated Electoress Sophia of Hanover (granddaughter of James I and VI) as Anne's successor, if Anne died childless.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The Act of Security granted the Parliament of Scotland, the three Estates, the right to choose a successor and explicitly required a choice different from the English monarch unless the English were to grant free trade and navigation.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Then the Alien Act 1705 was passed in the English parliament, designating Scots in England as "foreign nationals" and blocking about half of all Scottish trade by boycotting exports to England or its colonies, unless Scotland came back to negotiate a Union.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] To encourage a union, "honours, appointments, pensions and even arrears of pay and other expenses were distributed to clinch support from Scottish peers and MPs".
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The Scottish economy was severely impacted by privateers during the 1688–1697 Nine Years' War and the 1701 War of the Spanish Succession, with the Royal Navy focusing on protecting English ships.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] This compounded the economic pressure caused by the Darien scheme, and the seven ill years of the 1690s, when 5–15% of the population died of starvation.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The Scottish Parliament was promised financial assistance, protection for its maritime trade, and an end to economic restrictions on trade with England.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The votes of the Court party, influenced by Queen Anne's favourite, James Douglas, 2nd Duke of Queensberry, combined with the majority of the Squadrone Volante, were sufficient to ensure passage of the treaty.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The role played by bribery has long been debated. £20,000 was distributed by David Boyle, 1st Earl of Glasgow, of which 60% went to the Duke of Queensberry, the Queen's Commissioner in Parliament.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Another negotiator, John Campbell, 2nd Duke of Argyll was given an English dukedom.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Professor Sir Tom Devine agreed that promises of "favours, sinecures, pensions, offices and straightforward cash bribes became indispensable to secure government majorities".
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] As for representation going forwards, Scotland was, in the new united parliament, only to get 45 MPs, one more than Cornwall, and only 16 (unelected) peers in the House of Lords.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] There were mixed opinions in Scotland about the prospect of a union with England.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Sir George Lockhart of Carnwath, the only Scottish negotiator to oppose Union, noted "the whole nation appears against (it)".
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Another negotiator, Sir John Clerk of Penicuik, who was an ardent Unionist, observed it was "contrary to the inclinations of at least three-fourths of the Kingdom".
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] As the seat of the Scottish Parliament, demonstrators in Edinburgh feared the impact of its loss on the local economy.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Elsewhere, there was widespread concern about the independence of the kirk, and possible tax rises.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Virtually all of the print discourses of 1699–1706 spoke against incorporating union, creating the conditions for widespread rejection of the treaty in 1706 and 1707.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] In the wake of unionist proselytising in the autumn of 1706 and early 1707, many Scots were undecided about the prospect of a union.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Rather, there was considerably more support in Scotland for a federal union with England than an incorporative one, similar to the devolved Scottish parliament that would be established within Britain nearly three centuries later.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] As the treaty passed through the Parliament of Scotland, opposition was voiced by petitions from shires, burghs, presbyteries and parishes.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] According to Christopher Whatley, however, calls for a union with England began in Scotland itself in the 1690s for the purpose of safeguarding the law, line of succession, and to improve the economy.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Ireland, though a kingdom under the same crown, was not included in the union.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] It remained a separate kingdom, unrepresented in Parliament, and was legally subordinate to Great Britain until the Renunciation Act 1783.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] In July 1707 each House of the Parliament of Ireland passed a congratulatory address to Queen Anne, praying that "May God put it in your royal heart to add greater strength and lustre to your crown, by a still more comprehensive Union".
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The British government did not respond to the invitation and an equal union between Great Britain and Ireland was out of consideration until the 1790s.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The union with Ireland finally came about on 1 January 1801.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Deeper political integration had been a key policy of Queen Anne from the time she acceded to the throne in 1702.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Under the aegis of the Queen and her ministers in both kingdoms, the parliaments of England and Scotland (the **Act for a Treaty with England 1705**) agreed to participate in fresh negotiations for a union treaty in 1705.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Both countries appointed 31 commissioners to conduct the negotiations.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Most of the Scottish commissioners favoured union, and about half were government ministers and other officials.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] At the head of the list was the Duke of Queensberry, and the Lord Chancellor of Scotland, the Earl of Seafield.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The English commissioners included the Lord High Treasurer, Sidney Godolphin, 1st Earl of Godolphin, the Lord Keeper of the Great Seal, William Cowper, Baron Cowper, and a large number of Whigs who supported union.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Tories were not in favour of union and only one was represented among the commissioners.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Negotiations between the English and Scottish commissioners took place between 16 April and 22 July 1706 at the Cockpit in London.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Each side had its own particular concerns.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] After negotiations ended in July 1706, the acts had to be ratified by both Parliaments.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] In Scotland, about 100 of the 227 members of the Parliament of Scotland were supportive of the Court Party.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] For extra votes the pro-court side could rely on about 25 members of the Squadrone Volante, led by the James Graham, 4th Marquess of Montrose and John Ker, 1st Duke of Roxburghe.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The Court party enjoyed significant funding from England and the Treasury and included many who had accumulated debts following the Darien Disaster.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The act ratifying the Treaty of Union was finally carried in the Parliament of Scotland by 110 votes to 69 on 16 January 1707, with a number of key amendments.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] News of the ratification and of the amendments was received in Westminster, where the Act was passed quickly through both Houses and received the royal assent on 6 March.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Though the English Act was later in date, it bore the year '1706' while Scotland's was '1707', as the legal year in England began only on 25 March.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] In Scotland, the Duke of Queensberry was largely responsible for the successful passage of the Union act by the Parliament of Scotland.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] In Scotland, he was greeted by stones and eggs but in England he was cheered for his action.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] He had personally received around half of the funding awarded by the Westminster Treasury.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] In April 1707, he travelled to London to attend celebrations at the royal court, and was greeted by groups of noblemen and gentry lined along the road.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] From Barnet, the route was lined with crowds of cheering people, and once he reached London a huge crowd had formed.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] On 17 April, the Duke was gratefully received by the Queen at Kensington Palace and the Acts came into effect on 1 May 1707.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] A day of thanksgiving was declared in England and Ireland but not in Scotland, where the bells of St Giles rang out the tune of *"why should I be so sad on my wedding day"*.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The Treaty of Union, agreed between representatives of the Parliament of England and the Parliament of Scotland in 1706, consisted of 25 articles, 15 of which were economic in nature.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] In Scotland, each article was voted on separately and several clauses in articles were delegated to specialised subcommittees.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Article 1 of the treaty was based on the political principle of an incorporating union and this was secured by a majority of 116 votes to 83 on 4 November 1706.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] To minimise the opposition of the Church of Scotland, an Act was also passed to secure the Presbyterian establishment of the Church, after which the Church stopped its open opposition, although hostility remained at lower levels of the clergy.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The treaty as a whole was finally ratified on 16 January 1707 by a majority of 110 votes to 69.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The two Acts incorporated provisions for Scotland to send representative peers from the Peerage of Scotland to sit in the House of Lords.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] It guaranteed that the Church of Scotland would remain the established church in Scotland, that the Court of Session would "remain in all time coming within Scotland", and that Scots law would "remain in the same force as before".
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Other provisions included the restatement of the Act of Settlement 1701 and the ban on Roman Catholics from taking the throne.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] It also created a customs union and monetary union.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The Act provided that any "laws and statutes" that were "contrary to or inconsistent with the terms" of the Act would "cease and become void".
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The Scottish Parliament also passed the Protestant Religion and Presbyterian Church Act 1707 guaranteeing the status of the Presbyterian Church of Scotland.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The English Parliament passed a similar Act, 6 Ann. c.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] 40—later named the Union with Scotland (Amendment) Act 1707—united the Privy Council of England and Privy Council of Scotland and decentralised Scottish administration by appointing justices of the peace in each shire to carry out administration.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] In effect it took the day-to-day government of Scotland out of the hands of politicians and into those of the College of Justice.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] On 18 December 1707 the Act for better Securing the Duties of East India Goods was passed which extended the monopoly of the East India Company to Scotland.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] In the year following the Union, the Treason Act 1708 abolished the Scottish law of treason and extended the corresponding English law across Great Britain.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Clark, gaining "freedom of trade with England and the colonies" as well as "a great expansion of markets".
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The agreement guaranteed the permanent status of the Presbyterian church in Scotland, and the separate system of laws and courts in Scotland.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] However, the Scottish economy was lagging behind not only from the impact of wars, but also because of chronic deflation and industrial underdevelopment.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Scotland remained a predominantly agrarian society, and the lack of manpower caused by previous conflicts contributed to an underwhelming agricultural output, which intermittently escalated into local food shortages or famines.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] In turn, the overreliance of Scottish landowners on foreign goods led to a deficit of financial capital, as gold and silver were exported overseas and deflation occurred.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The Scottish Parliament attempted to combat the issue by attracting foreign investment; duty on ship building materials was lifted, taxes on new manufacturing stocks were cut, and customs on textile and linen goods were removed.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Scotland grew increasingly dependent on its linen industry, which became the biggest source of employment after agriculture and constituted one-third of Scottish industry.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Continental linen industries could outcompete Scotland, and protectionist tariffs implemented by Scotland led to tariff wars as European countries closed their markets to Scotland.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] In this situation, England became the largest foreign market for Scottish linen; however, while the tariffs in place shielded Scotland from the much larger English industry, England also retaliated against them.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] This forced Scotland to seek economic alternatives.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] At the time, trade with colonies was rapidly growing in importance in Europe, and trade with colonies was very attractive to Scotland, given its pastoral economy.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] American colonies had a high demand of agricultural goods such as leather skins of goats and sheep, which would have provided Scotland a valuable source of income.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Search for colonial trade, along with the frustration caused by economic and political rivalry with England, led to the Darien scheme – an unsuccessful attempt to establish a Scottish colony in the Gulf of Darién.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The failure of the Darien scheme led to a financial crisis in Scotland.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The high cost of its project exacerbated the deflation in Scotland.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The Bank of Scotland had dangerously low reserves, and in early 1700s a run on the bank occurred, along with temporary suspension of business.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Ultimately, the Scottish bank managed to stay solvent, although the persisting deflation and low reserves largely contributed to the feeling of Scottish economy being in a precarious position.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Economist Aida Ramos argues that the Darien scheme could have succeeded if it was to receive support from either England or Spain, and that it lacked the capability to create a threat to England or its interests.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] According to Ramos, the English intervention against the scheme was to meet the expansionary aims of England, as to ensure both its colonial dominance as well as the annexation of Scotland.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] By 1703, the Scottish government was highly disillusioned with the union, and many believed that the only way to let the Scottish economy flourish was to separate from England.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Scotland would try to establish further autonomy from England with the Act of Security 1704, which provoked a retaliation from England – Scottish ministers were bribed, and Alien Act 1705 was passed.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] According to the Alien Act, unless Scotland appointed commissioners to negotiate for union by Christmas, every Scot in England would be treated as an alien, leading to the confiscation of their English estates.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Additionally, Scottish wares were to be banned from England.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The Scottish economy was now facing a crisis, and the parliament was polarised into pro-union and anti-union factions, with the former led by Daniel Defoe.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] The unionists stressed how important trade with England is to the Scottish economy, and seen trade with continental Europe as not beneficial.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] They argued that the Scottish economy could survive by trading with England, and sanctions that would result from the Alien Act would collapse the economy.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] For Defoe, joining the union would not only prevent the Alien Act, but also remove additional limitations and regulations and lead Scotland to prosperity.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Anti-unionists questioned the English goodwill and criticised the unionist faction for submitting to the English blackmail.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] They argued that Scotland could make a recovery by trading with the Netherlands, Spain and Norway, allowing Scotland to diversify its own industries as well.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] They argued that the union would make Scotland unable to conduct independent trade policy, meaning that any possibility to remove the flaws in Scottish economy would be gone forever, which would turn Scotland into a "mere satellite of the richer kingdom".
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Ultimately, Scottish ministers voted in favour of the union, despite the lack of public support, with the overwhelming majority of the Scottish population at the time protesting vociferously against any union with England.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Many Scots considered themselves to have been betrayed by their own elites, and that the union bill was able to pass only thanks to English bribery.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] In the first few decades after the union, England did not end up becoming the main trading partner of Scotland, as other European powers became the primary source of imported goods for Scotland.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] For at least the first 40 years after the union, Scotland persisted in its traditional trade patterns, and the economic situation of Scotland was not as dire as that described in the months leading up to the Acts of Union.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] Christopher Whatley writes, however, that by 1799, it was reported that the union of Scotland with England had not only benefitted the Scottish economy, but promoted a "commercial prosperity" unknown to any people.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/acts-of-union-1707] A commemorative two-pound coin was issued to mark the tercentennial—300th anniversary—of the Union, which occurred two days before the Scottish Parliament general election on 3 May 2007.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/advocate-general-for-scotland] The **Office of the Advocate General for Scotland** is a ministerial department of the Government of the United Kingdom.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/advocate-general-for-scotland] The position is currently occupied by Catherine Smith, Baroness Smith of Cluny.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/advocate-general-for-scotland] The office of Advocate General for Scotland was created in 1999 by the Scotland Act 1998 to be the chief legal adviser to the United Kingdom Government on Scots law.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/advocate-general-for-scotland] This function had previously been carried out by the Lord Advocate and Solicitor General for Scotland, who were transferred to the Scottish Government on the establishment of the Scottish Parliament.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/advocate-general-for-scotland] The office of the Advocate General for Scotland should not be confused with that of "His Majesty's Advocate", which is the term used for the Lord Advocate in Scottish criminal proceedings.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/advocate-general-for-scotland] The first holder of the office was Lynda Clark, then Member of Parliament for Edinburgh Pentlands and from 2005 a member of the House of Lords as Baroness Clark of Calton.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/advocate-general-for-scotland] On 18 January 2006, Baroness Clark resigned to take up office as a Senator of the College of Justice, a judge of the Supreme Courts of Scotland.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/advocate-general-for-scotland] The office was then vacant until 15 March of that year when, under section 87 of the Scotland Act 1998, its functions were temporarily conferred on the Secretary of State for Scotland, Alistair Darling MP, himself a Scottish advocate.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/advocate-general-for-scotland] There had been substantial criticism from the judiciary and others of the length of time the office had been left vacant.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/advocate-general-for-scotland] On 21 March, however, it was announced Neil Davidson, former Solicitor General for Scotland, had been appointed Advocate General.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/advocate-general-for-scotland] He was created a life peer, as Baron Davidson of Glen Clova, on 22 March 2006.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/advocate-general-for-scotland] On 14 May 2010, Jim Wallace, Baron Wallace of Tankerness, a former Deputy First Minister of Scotland, was appointed by the coalition government.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/advocate-general-for-scotland] Richard Keen was appointed Advocate General in David Cameron's majority government on 29 May 2015, and has retained the post through two subsequent prime ministers to 2020.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/advocate-general-for-scotland] He was created a life peer, as Baron Keen of Elie, on 8 June 2015.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/advocate-general-for-scotland] He resigned on 16 September 2020 citing concerns arising from the UK Internal Market Bill, noting in his letter of resignation to Boris Johnson that he found it "increasingly difficult to reconcile what I consider to be my obligations as a Law Officer with your policy intentions".
[src:conservation-in-scotland/advocate-general-for-scotland] Keith Stewart was appointed to succeed Keen on 15 October 2020.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/advocate-general-for-scotland] Catherine Smith was appointed to the office and a life peerage by the Starmer government on 29 August 2024.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/advocate-general-for-scotland] All staff are on secondment or loan from other government organisations, mainly the Scottish Government and the Ministry of Justice.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] In comparison, reforestation means re-establishing forest that have either been cut down or lost due to natural causes, such as fire, storm, etc.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] Nowadays, the boundaries between afforestation and reforestation projects can be blurred as it may not be so clear what was there before at what point in time.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] An essential aspect of successful afforestation efforts lies in the careful selection of tree species that are well-suited to the local climate and soil conditions.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] By choosing appropriate species, afforested areas can better withstand the impacts of climate change.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] Earth offers enough room to plant an additional 0.9 billion ha of tree canopy cover.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] Planting and protecting them would sequester 205 billion tons of carbon which is about 20 years of current global carbon emissions.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] This level of sequestration would represent about 25% of the atmosphere's current carbon pool.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] However, there has been debate about whether afforestation is beneficial for the sustainable use of natural resources, with some researchers pointing out that tree planting is not the only way to enhance climate mitigation and CO2 capture.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] Non-forest areas, such as grasslands and savannas, also benefit the biosphere and humanity, and they need a different management strategy - they are not supposed to be forests.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] Afforestation critics argue that ecosystems without trees are not necessarily degraded, and many of them can store carbon as they are; for example, savannas and tundra store carbon underground.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] Carbon sequestration estimates in these areas often do not include the total amount of carbon reductions in soils and slowing tree growth over time.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] Afforestation can also negatively affect biodiversity by increasing fragmentation and edge effects on the habitat outside the planted area.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] Australia, Canada, China, India, Israel, United States and Europe have afforestation programs to increase carbon dioxide removal in forests and in some cases to reduce desertification.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] The term afforestation means establishing new forest on lands that were not forest before (e.g. abandoned agriculture).
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] The same definition in other words states that afforestation is "conversion to forest of land that historically has not contained forests".
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] In comparison, reforestation means the "conversion to forest of land that has previously contained forests but that has been converted to some other use".
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] Agroforestry (this is essentially an agricultural activity carried out in order to grow harvestable crops such as fruits and nuts).
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] Tree plantations (carried out in order to produce wood and wood-pulp products; this can be seen as an alternative to cutting down naturally occurring forests).
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] However, the term *afforestation* can also "imply the intentional conversion of native non-forest ecosystems to exotic tree cover and violate biodiversity safeguards".
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] The process of afforestation begins with site selection.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] Several environmental factors of the site must be analyzed, including climate, soil, vegetation, and human activity.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] These factors will determine the quality of the site, what species of trees should be planted, and what planting method should be used.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] After the forest site has been assessed, the area must be prepared for planting.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] Preparation can involve a variety of mechanical or chemical methods, such as chopping, mounding, bedding, herbicides, and prescribed burning.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] Once the site is prepared, planting can take place.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] One method for planting is direct seeding, which involves sowing seeds directly into the forest floor.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] Another is seedling planting, which is similar to direct seeding except that seedlings already have an established root system.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] Afforestation by cutting is an option for tree species that can reproduce asexually, where a piece of a tree stem, branch, root, or leaves can be planted onto the forest floor and sprout successfully.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] Sometimes special tools, such as a tree planting bar, are used to make planting of trees easier and faster.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] There are several benefits from afforestation such as carbon sequestration, increasing rainfall, prevention of topsoil erosion (from water and wind), flood and landslide mitigation, barriers against high winds, shelter for wildlife, employment and alternative sources of wood products.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] Afforestation projects create employment opportunities, particularly in rural areas, thus promoting sustainable livelihoods.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] They can create many jobs in various forest-related activities.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] Forests are an important part of the global carbon cycle because trees and plants absorb carbon dioxide through photosynthesis.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] Therefore, they play an important role in climate change mitigation.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] By removing the greenhouse gas CO2 from the air, forests function as terrestrial carbon sinks, meaning they store large amounts of carbon in the form of biomass, encompassing roots, stems, branches, and leaves.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] By doing so, forests sequester approximately 25% of human carbon emissions annually, playing a critical role in Earth's climate.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] Throughout their lifespan, trees continue to sequester carbon, storing atmospheric CO2 long-term.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] Sustainable forest management, afforestation, reforestation are therefore important contributions to climate change mitigation.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] An important consideration in such efforts is that forests can turn from sinks to carbon sources.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] In 2019 forests took up a third less carbon than they did in the 1990s, due to higher temperatures, droughts and deforestation.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] National-scale forest inventory data also shows trends from 1999 to 2020 that some forests were already approaching climate thresholds shifting them from carbon sinks to carbon sources.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] The typical tropical forest may become a carbon source by the 2060s.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] Researchers have found that, in terms of environmental services, it is better to avoid deforestation than to allow for deforestation to subsequently reforest, as the latter leads to irreversible effects in terms of biodiversity loss and soil degradation.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] Furthermore, the probability that legacy carbon will be released from soil is higher in a younger boreal forest.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] In particular, boreal forests have been noted to support the growth of Armillaria (honey fungus), which is a root pathogen that breaks down compounds necessary for wood integrity, increasing the likelihood of carbon release.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] Global greenhouse gas emissions caused by damage to tropical rainforests may have been substantially underestimated until around 2019.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] Additionally, the effects of afforestation and reforestation will be farther in the future than keeping existing forests intact.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] It takes much longer − several decades − for the benefits for global warming to manifest to the same carbon sequestration benefits from mature trees in tropical forests and hence from limiting deforestation.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] Therefore, scientists consider "the protection and recovery of carbon-rich and long-lived ecosystems, especially natural forests" to be "the major climate solution".
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] The planting of trees on marginal crop and pasture lands helps to incorporate carbon from atmospheric CO 2 into biomass.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] For this carbon sequestration process to succeed the carbon must not return to the atmosphere from biomass burning or rotting when the trees die.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] Several species of *Ficus* such as *Ficus wakefieldii* have been observed to sequester atmospheric CO2 as calcium oxalate in the presence of oxalotrophic bacteria and fungi, which catabolize the oxalate, which produces calcium carbonate.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] The calcium carbonate is precipitated throughout the tree, which also alkalinizes the surrounding soil.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] These species are current candidates for carbon sequestration in agroforestry.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] This Calcium-oxalate fixation process was first observed in the *Iroko* tree, which can sequester up to a ton of calcium carbonate in the soil over its lifespan.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] Also Cacti, such as the *Saguaro*, transfer carbon from the biological cycle to the geological cycle by forming the mineral calcium carbonate.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] Earth offers enough room to plant an additional 0.9 billion ha of tree canopy cover, although this estimate has been criticized, and the true area that has a net cooling effect on the climate when accounting for biophysical feedbacks like albedo is 20-80% lower.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] Planting and protecting these trees would sequester 205 billion tons of carbon if the trees survive future climate stress to reach maturity.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] To put this number into perspective, this is about 20 years of current global carbon emissions (as of 2019) .
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] This level of sequestration would represent about 25% of the atmosphere's carbon pool in 2019.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] Life expectancy of forests varies throughout the world, influenced by tree species, site conditions, and natural disturbance patterns.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] In some forests, carbon may be stored for centuries, while in other forests, carbon is released with frequent stand replacing fires.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] Forests that are harvested prior to stand replacing events allow for the retention of carbon in manufactured forest products such as lumber.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] However, only a portion of the carbon removed from logged forests ends up as durable goods and buildings.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] The remainder ends up as sawmill by-products such as pulp, paper, and pallets.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] If all new construction globally utilized 90% wood products, largely via adoption of mass timber in low rise construction, this could sequester 700 million net tons of carbon per year.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] This is in addition to the elimination of carbon emissions from the displaced construction material such as steel or concrete, which are carbon-intense to produce.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] A meta-analysis found that mixed species plantations would increase carbon storage alongside other benefits of diversifying planted forests.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] Although a bamboo forest stores less total carbon than a mature forest of trees, a bamboo plantation sequesters carbon at a much faster rate than a mature forest or a tree plantation.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] Therefore, the farming of bamboo timber may have significant carbon sequestration potential.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] The Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO) reported that: "The total carbon stock in forests decreased from 668 gigatonnes in 1990 to 662 gigatonnes in 2020".
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] In Canada's boreal forests as much as 80% of the total carbon is stored in the soils as dead organic matter.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] Impacts on temperature are affected by the location of the forest.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] For example, reforestation in boreal or subarctic regions has less impact on climate.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] This is because it substitutes a high-albedo, snow-dominated region with a lower-albedo forest canopy.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] By contrast, tropical reforestation projects lead to a positive change such as the formation of clouds.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] These clouds then reflect the sunlight, lowering temperatures.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] Planting trees in tropical climates with wet seasons has another advantage.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] In such a setting, trees grow more quickly (fixing more carbon) because they can grow year-round.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] Trees in tropical climates have, on average, larger, brighter, and more abundant leaves than non-tropical climates.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] A study of the girth of 70,000 trees across Africa has shown that tropical forests fix more carbon dioxide pollution than previously realized.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] The research suggested almost one-fifth of fossil fuel emissions are absorbed by forests across Africa, Amazonia and Asia.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] Afforestation provides other environmental benefits, including increasing the soil quality and its organic carbon levels, reducing the risk of erosion and desertification.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] The planting of trees in urban areas is also able to reduce air pollution via the trees' absorption and filtration of pollutants, including carbon monoxide, sulfur dioxide, and ozone, in addition to CO2.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] Afforestation protects the biodiversity of plants and animals which allows the sustenance of ecosystems that provide clean air, soil fertilization, etc.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] Forests support biodiversity conservation, providing habitats for about 80% of the world's biodiversity and contributing to ecosystem restoration and resilience.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] Water management can be improved afforestation, as trees regulate hydrological cycles, reduce soil erosion, and prevent water runoff.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] Their capacity to capture and store water helps in mitigating floods and droughts.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] Forests act as natural air filters, absorbing pollutants and improving air quality.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] Urban forestation projects have been successful in reducing respiratory illnesses and enhancing overall air quality in cities.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] Trees provide shade and cooling effects.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] By shading and evaporation, forests can lower local temperatures, offering a more comfortable environment in urban areas and reducing the impact of extreme heat.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] Tree-planting campaigns are criticised for sometimes targeting areas where forests would not naturally occur, such as grassland and savanna biomes.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] Carbon sequestration forecasts of afforestation programmes often insufficiently consider possible carbon reductions in soils as well as slowing tree growth over time.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] Afforestation can negatively affect biodiversity through increasing fragmentation and edge effects for the habitat remaining outside the planted area.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] New forest plantations can introduce generalist predators that would otherwise not be found in open habitat into the covered area, which could detrimentally increase predation rates on the native species of the area.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] A study by scientists at the British Trust for Ornithology into the decline of British populations of Eurasian curlew found that afforestation had impacted curlew populations through fragmentation of their naturally open grassland habitats and increases in generalist predators.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] Questions have also been raised in the scientific community regarding how global afforestation could affect the surface albedo of Earth.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] The canopy cover of mature trees could make the surface albedo darker, which causes more heat to be absorbed, potentially raising the temperature of the planet.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] This is particularly relevant in parts of the world with high levels of snow cover, due to the significant difference in albedo between highly reflective white snow and darker forest cover which absorbs more solar radiation.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] One significant criticism of reforestation or afforestation efforts that rely on monocultures of - usually conifer - trees is that, while they may increase tree cover, they fail to provide the diverse and complex habitat needed by most woodland creatures.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] Monocultures, often planted for commercial purposes or ease of management, lack the biodiversity of natural forests.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] These single-species forests provide limited food sources, shelter, and nesting sites for a wide range of wildlife, and in purely coniferous forests low levels of light may reach the forest floor reducing habitat and variety of plant life.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] Many woodland creatures, such as birds, mammals, and insects, rely on a variety of tree species and plant life for survival, and the uniformity of monocultures does not support these varied ecological needs.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] As a result, such reforestation or afforestation efforts may unintentionally create environments that are unsuitable for the very species they aim to protect, thus undermining broader conservation goals.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] The Great Green Wall of Africa is a ~5,000 mile forest being planted across the continent to stop the spread of the Sahara Desert to the south.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] In Adelaide, South Australia (a city of 1.3 million as of June 2016), Premier Mike Rann (2002 to 2011) launched an urban forest initiative in 2003 to plant 3 million native trees and shrubs by 2014 on 300 project sites across the metro area.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] Thousands of Adelaide citizens participated in community planting days on sites including parks, reserves, transport corridors, schools, water courses and coastline.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] Only native trees were planted to ensure genetic integrity.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] Rann said the project aimed to beautify and cool the city and make it more livable, improve air and water quality, and reduce Adelaide's greenhouse gas emissions by 600,000 tonnes of CO2 per year.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] In 2003, the government of Canada created a four-year project called the Forest 2020 Plantation Development and Assessment Initiative, which involved planting 6000 ha of fast-growing forests on non-forested lands countrywide.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] These plantations were used to analyze how afforestation can help to increase carbon sequestration and mitigate greenhouse gas (GHG) emissions while also considering the economic and investment attractiveness of afforestation.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] On 14 December 2020, Canada's Minister of Natural Resources Seamus O'Regan announced the federal government's investment of $3.16 billion to plant two billion trees over the next 10 years.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] This plan aims to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by an estimated 12 megatonnes by 2050.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] China had the highest afforestation rate of any country or region in the world, with 4.77 million hectares (47,000 square kilometers) of afforestation in 2008.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] According to the 2021 government work report, forest coverage will reach 24 percent based on the main targets and tasks for the 14th Five-Year Plan period.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] A law in China from 1981 requires that every school student over the age of 11 plants at least one tree per year.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] From 2011 to 2016, the city Dongying in Shandong province forested over 13,800 hectares of saline soil through the Shandong Ecological Afforestation Project, which was launched with support from the World Bank.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] In 2017, the Saihanba Afforestation Community won the UN Champions of the Earth Award in the Inspiration and Action category for "transforming degraded land into a lush paradise".
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] The successful afforestation of the Loess Plateau involved collaborative efforts by international and domestic professionals alongside villagers.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] Through this initiative, millions of villagers across four of China's poorest provinces were able to improve farming practices and increase incomes and employment, alleviating poverty.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] In addition, the careful selection of trees ensured a healthy, self-sustainable ecosystem between tree and soil which facilitated a net carbon sink.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] The Loess Plateau, although successful, was costly, reaching almost US$500 million.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] This contrasts with more recent initiatives where the results have not been as favorable.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] In an attempt to make afforestation both low-cost and less time-consuming, China shifted towards monoculture of mostly red pine trees.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] However, this did not adequately take into consideration environmental structure and led to increased soil erosion, desertification, sand/dust storms and short-lived trees.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] This has reduced China's environmental sustainability index (ESI) to one of the lowest in the world.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] Regarding the effects of afforestation on long-term carbon stocks and carbon sequestration these decrease when trees are less than 5 years old and increase quickly thereafter.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] This means trees from monoculture planting that do not survive never reach full potential for carbon sequestration to offset China's carbon output.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] Overall, there is a possibility for afforestation to balance carbon levels and aid carbon neutrality, but several challenges still remain which hinder an all encompassing effort.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] The Chinese government requires mining companies to restore the environment around exhausted mines by refilling excavated pits and planting crops or trees.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] Many mining companies use these recovered mines for ecotourism business.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] Europe deforested more than half of its forested areas over the last 6000 years.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] The European Union (EU) has paid farmers for afforestation since 1990, offering grants to turn farmland into forest and payments for the management of forest.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] As part of the Green Deal, the EU program "3 Billion Tree Planting Pledge by 2030" provides direction on afforestation of previous farmland in addition to reforestation.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] According to Food and Agriculture Organization statistics, Spain had the third fastest afforestation rate in Europe in the 1990–2005 period, after Iceland and Ireland.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] In those years, a total of 44,360 square kilometers were afforested, and the total forest cover rose from 13.5 to 17.9 million hectares.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] In 1990, forests covered 26.6% of the Spanish territory.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] As of 2007, that figure had risen to 36.6%.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] Spain today has the fifth largest forest area in the European Union.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] As of 2023 the total forest and tree cover in India was 22%.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] The forests of India are grouped into 5 major categories and 16 types based on biophysical criteria.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] 38% of the forest is categorized as subtropical dry deciduous and 30% as tropical moist deciduous and other smaller groups.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] In 2016 the Indian government passed the CAMPA (Compensatory Afforestation Fund Management and Planning Authority) law, allowing about 40 thousand crores rupees (almost $6 Billion) to go to Indian states for planting trees.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] In 2016 the Maharashtra government planted almost 20,000,000 saplings and pledged to plant another 30,000,000 the following year.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] In 2019, 220 million trees were planted in a single day in the Indian state of Uttar Pradesh.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] With wood production as a main objective, monocultures of Aleppo pine were vigorously planted between 1948 and the 1970s.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] Following a massive collapse of this species in the 1990s, due to attacks by the insect pine blast scale, the Aleppo pine was gradually replaced by Pinus brutia.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] Since the 1990s there has been a trend towards more ecological approaches planting mixed forests combining pines with broadleaf Mediterranean species e.g. oak, pistachio, carob, olive, arbutus and buckthorn.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] About 250 million trees have been planted through the JNF across Israel since 1990.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] Tree coverage increased from 2% in 1948 to over 8% at present.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] The Japanese temperate rainforest is well sustained and maintains a high biodiversity.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] One method that has been utilized in maintaining the health of forests in Japan has been afforestation.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] The Japanese government and private businesses have set up multiple projects to plant native tree species in open areas scattered throughout the country.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] This practice has resulted in shifts in forest structure and a healthy temperate rainforest that maintains a high biodiversity.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] In January 2013, the UK government set a target of 12% woodland cover in England by 2060, up from the then 10%.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] In Wales the National Assembly for Wales has set a target of 19% woodland cover, up from 15%.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] Government-backed initiatives such as the Woodland Carbon Code are intended to support this objective by encouraging corporations and landowners to create new woodland to offset their carbon emissions.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] Charitable groups such as Trees for Life (Scotland) contribute to afforestation and reforestation efforts in the UK.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] Afforestation efforts in Scotland have provided an increase in woodland expansion.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] By the 20th century mark, Scotland had diminished woodland coverage to 5% of Scotland's land area.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] However, by the early 21st century, afforestation efforts have increased woodland coverage to 17%.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] The Scottish government released their Draft Climate Change Plan in January 2017.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] The 2017 draft plan has increased the targeted woodland coverage to 21% by 2032 and increases the afforestation rate to 15,000 hectares per year.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] In the 1800s people moving westward in the US encountered the Great Plains – land with fertile soil, a growing population and a demand for timber but with few trees to supply it.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] So tree planting was encouraged along homesteads.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] Arbor Day was founded in 1872 by Julius Sterling Morton in Nebraska City.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] By the 1930s the Dust Bowl environmental disaster signified a reason for adding significant new tree cover.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/afforestation] Public works programs under the New Deal saw the planting of 18,000 miles of windbreaks stretching from North Dakota to Texas to fight soil erosion (see Great Plains Shelterbelt).
[src:conservation-in-scotland/conservation-in-scotland] This article gives an overview of the structure of environmental and cultural **conservation in Scotland**, a constituent country of the United Kingdom.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/conservation-in-scotland] Upon the introduction of devolved government the environment and built heritage were not listed as reserved issues, and so for the most part conservation is the responsibility of the Scottish Parliament, the Scottish Government, and the public bodies that report to them.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/conservation-in-scotland] Although originally reserved, responsibility for all planning and nature conservation matters at sea up to 200 miles from the Scottish coast was transferred to the Scottish Government in 2008.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/conservation-in-scotland] Some matters related to conservation, such as international treaties and border controls on prohibited species, remain the responsibility of the UK Government.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/conservation-in-scotland] Much environment legislation in Scotland is based on the adoption into Scots law of European Union directives, such as the Habitats Directive.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/conservation-in-scotland] As such there may be changes to the structure and nature of conservation activities in Scotland following the UK's departure from the European Union.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/conservation-in-scotland] The following are public bodies of the Scottish Government, with notes on their areas of responsibility.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/conservation-in-scotland] Within the UK Government, environmental protection is the responsibility of the Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs (DEFRA).
[src:conservation-in-scotland/conservation-in-scotland] Many non-governmental organisations are active in conservation issues in Scotland.
[src:conservation-in-scotland/conservation-in-scotland] The following list provides some examples.
